&#xa0;[bold]Hammersmith &amp; Fulham Council – Written evidence[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1[bold]              [bold]Preamble[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The first Call for Evidence is an open call that also contains 23 specific questions.  These are largely of a technical and legal nature and either address specific aspects of the legislative process or focus on areas that are not of direct relevance to the role of Hammersmith &amp; Fulham as a local authority or to the exercising of its functions.  However, there are elements of the draft legislation that are of concern to us and our specific comments in relation to these are below.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2[bold]              [bold]Comments[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1[bold]              [bold]Erection of public statues in London – Clause 19[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]There is not a substantial demand for this in Hammersmith &amp; Fulham and so this is not considered by the authority to be a major issue.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2[bold]              [bold]Right to Buy – Clause 20[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Hammersmith &amp; Fulham Council is a long-standing supporter of the Right to Buy scheme and actively lobbied Government to increase the maximum discount in London, first to £75,000 and then to £100,000.  The Council therefore supports the proposal to reduce the qualifying period from five to three years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Council believes that increasing the eligibility criteria could kick-start Right to Buy and help thousands of hard-working people who could not otherwise even dream of owning a home.  Home ownership confers a sense of pride and empowerment.  However, for too long home ownership has been nothing but a pipedream for most of our tenants.  This Council has therefore long argued that, for the scheme to truly take-off in London, a £100,000 discount is needed, as well as opportunities to encourage other forms of shared ownership
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This borough has the fourth most expensive housing in the country and like the rest of the capital, needs to be treated as a special case for Right to 
[normal]Buy
[normal] to benefit a greater proportion of council tenants.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We are also working on a proposal to enable council tenants to purchase a share of their home. The intention is that this ‘Right to Buy Part 2’ will enable council tenants to purchase a percentage of the property below the minimum level offered as part of Social Home Buy and receive a proportionate discount.  The tenant would then pay the Council rent for the part of the home they do not own.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Right to 
[normal]Buy
[normal] receipts are spent on other affordable housing projects in the borough, such as low cost home ownership schemes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3[bold]              [bold]Reduction of duties relating to energy and climate change – Clause 27[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The repeals/amendments (with out-of-date elements being removed) and changes in relation to reporting requirements are supported by this authority.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4[bold]              [bold]Household waste: decriminalisation – Clause 29 and Schedule 10[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Hammersmith &amp; Fulham is one of the most densely populated local authority areas in the UK.  Section 46 of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 provides a Council with powers to serve a statutory notice on a residential occupier.  This notice provides stipulations regarding the presentation of waste receptacles.  This can cover the receptacle, receptacle positioning, timing, recycling, contamination, etc.  Once a notice has been served upon an occupier they are bound by the terms. There is a 21 day period for the person in receipt of a notice to appeal to the magistrates’ court. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Once bound by the terms of the notice, an occupier can be subject to prosecution or have liability discharged via the payment of a fixed penalty notice (FPN).  The current FPN level is £80.00 and the Council offers a £40 rate if the FPN is paid within 10 days.  The maximum fine, if found guilty in a magistrates’ court, is Level 3, which is £1,000.00.  In the view of this Council:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The current process is extremely efficient and effective, viz.:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The clause and schedule in the draft Deregulation Bill will, if enacted, lengthen this process and render it almost unenforceable.  The process would become as follows:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Section 46 of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 is used in a proportionate, justifiable and transparent way by this Council and it has led to success in improving waste presentation throughout the Borough.  It also provides a strong educational vehicle to promote correct waste presentation and reduce contamination in recycling.  Responsible use of Section 46 means all parties benefit and our objectives of cleaner streets are achieved.  These changes to Section 46 will adversely affect the ability of local authorities to tackle waste offences in a robust manner.  Accordingly this Council objects to the proposed changes to Section 46 of the Environmental Protection Act 1990.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5[bold]              [bold]Reducing burdens on schools – Clause 33[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The changes in the responsibility for setting school dates may lead to difficulties for parents with children in more than one school.  Hammersmith &amp; Fulham’s experience has been that schools and families welcome a local authority co-ordinated approach and will probably continue to seek this advice.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6[bold]              [bold]Housing strategies – Clause 21[bold]Sustainable Community Strategy – Clause 44[bold]Local Area Agreements – Clause 45[bold]Duties to consult and involve – Clause 47[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Council also supports the proposals to remove the requirements to produce the sustainable community strategy and housing strategy and the removal of the duty to consult and involve.  In September 2010, the Council suggested to central Government that it should remove the strategy requirements in a bid to free local authorities from onerous reporting requirements.  This Council has long argued that top-performing local authorities need to be given greater freedom to concentrate on delivering value for the taxpayer and providing excellent services, rather than getting bogged-down producing lengthy, technical and bureaucratic documents.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Draft Deregulation Bill briefing[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Background[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The draft Deregulation Bill was published on 1 July 2013 by Kenneth Clarke, the Minister without Portfolio, and Oliver 
[normal]Letwin
[normal], the Minister for Government Policy.  The draft Bill amends or repeals 182 different pieces of legislation, removing unnecessary burdens on three key groups: businesses, individuals and public bodies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Joint Committee on the draft Deregulation Bill, chaired by Lord Rooker, was appointed by both Houses of Parliament on 17 July to conduct pre-legislative scrutiny into the draft Deregulation Bill and the policies underpinning it.  The Joint Committee comprises six MPs and six Peers.  It will take written and oral evidence and is required to make its report to both Houses by 16 December 2013.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Its first Call for Evidence, focusing principally on the generic provision and general questions about the draft Bill, was published on 29 July.  The deadline for responses is 16 September.  The call is attached as Annex 2 to this briefing.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Key relevant provisions[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The key provisions of interest to local government are as follows:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There are also provisions of indirect interest to local government, such as:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]September 2013
[normal]&#xa0;
